Data Source

The information that I will use for my final project is provided by the Massachusetts Department of Transportation, or MassDOT for short. MassDOT provides public access to a Transportation Data Management System, which has multiple types of data: counts of vehicles per hour at a given location per day per month (volume), which way cars drive through a particular intersection (location: AET09 for Framingham-fr, AET10 for Cochituate-co, AET11 for Newton-ne, AET12 for pre Alston Interchange-pre, and AET13 for post Alston Interchange-po; direction: EB for East Bound or WB for West Bound), a range how fast cars traveled on average at given times (speed), and the type of vehicle traveling past the sensor (class). The data that I will focus on are located on different locations along the Massachusetts Turnpike (Mass Pike). In the previous quarter, I manually downloaded all the Excel files. In this quarter, using Jupyter Notebook to run a python script my Dad helped me write, I could download all the files automatically (As shown in the Downloading Data section). Using the readxl package, I was able to load the Excel files into tibbles, which I worked with using techniques learned in class so far. I downloaded several years worth of data for particular intersections by downloading the monthly reports available for a given year. Each monthly report has a similar name format from a python wget script that my Dad helped me engineer, which was a major improvement this time around. Instead of spending hours manually downloading everything, this python script goes through a list of locations, months, years, class, speed, and volume and stores the Excel files on my computer, where I can move them into the folder for my final project. I unfortunately do not have the time to investigate the elm_street, or Concord Rotary, location as I did last quarter.

Geography

One of the questions I had last quarter concerned how traffic behavior has changed after converting physical tollbooths into electronic ones on the Mass Pike. A company called Raytheon (a defense contractor based out of Waltham, MA) was paid 130 million dollars to convert the outdated toll booths into electronic tolls that are able to process cars with and without an EZ pass transponder. The hope was to reduce the risk of accidents from people slowing down and merging at toll booths and to the workers, as talked about in The Boston Globe. The plan to make toll booths electronic was unveiled in 2014, but not materialized until Friday October 28th, 2018 according to wbur. The result is shown in the image from CBS Boston. I was initially concerned with looking at the before and after adding electronic tolls, but I became more interested in seeing the difference between traffic prior to the coronavirus pandemic and traffic during the pandemic. If my models are good at predicting traffic patterns using cars_per_hour, then I can say that traffic unlikely changed during the pandemic. Conversely, as what I view as more likely, if my models are terrible at predicting traffic patterns via cars_per_hour, then I can say that the change in traffic was noticeable even to multiple models. When predicting the daily average speed of cars, if the model performs well, likely people are not travelling any faster or slower than they otherwise would. If the model does not perform well, then there is likely a difference in travel time for commuters. The locations I selected along the Mass Pike are also pictured below, using mapping techniques learned in STAT 302.

Why These Data

Choosing to look at traffic data for my final project in STAT 301-1 has really influenced me. I think it is because the data have a connection to my family and other families across the state with family members that commute to Boston (at least before the pandemic). Im interested to see if traffic has changed over time with the increasing registration of vehicles each year, and even more interested in seeing if I can quantify this change. I would also like to see if traffic has significantly improved with less cars on the road from more people working from home because of COVID. The common prescribed remedy for the ailment of rush hour traffic is congestion pricing. I want to see if in fact less cars on the road in 2020 has dramatically improved conditions. The main challenges for me have been processing the data based on volume, class, and speed from MassDOT and to make the right comparisons to properly analyze the data.

Downloading the Data

# Python Code:
import wget

years = list(range(2016,2021))
months = list(range(1,13))
location_list = ["AET09", "AET10", "AET11", "AET12", "AET13"]
direction_list = ["EB", "WB"]


for locationcode in location_list:
    for direction in direction_list:
        for year in years:
            for month in months:
                datecode = str(year)+"-"+str(month).zfill(2)+"-01"
                url_base = "https://mhd.ms2soft.com/tcds/file_download.aspx?agency_id=96&tcds_user_type="
                url_volume = url_base + "USER&format=excel&type=MonthlyVolume&abn=1&local_id=" + locationcode + "_" + direction + "&sdate=" + datecode
                url_speed = url_base + "USER&format=excel&type=MonthlyBin&i=8213126&abn=1&local_id=" + locationcode + "_" + direction + "&sdate=" + datecode +"&count_type=speed"
                url_class = url_base + "USER&format=excel&type=MonthlyBin&abn=1&local_id=" + locationcode + "_" + direction + "&sdate=" + datecode +"&count_type=class"
                wget.download(url_volume, 'c:/data/MonthlyVolumeReport_'+locationcode+"_"+direction+"_"+datecode+'.xlsx')
                wget.download(url_speed, 'c:/data/MonthlySpeedReport_'+locationcode+"_"+direction+"_"+datecode+'.xlsx')
                wget.download(url_class, 'c:/data/MonthlyClassReport_'+locationcode+"_"+direction+"_"+datecode+'.xlsx')




Initial Data Issues


After downloading my data, I was faced with the challenge of processing each of the data sets for class, speed, and volume. I had already been able to read in my data from my code last quarter for volume. The tricky part was reading in class and speed with bins of values spread across multiple lanes. Although it would be an interesting question to see if there is a difference in flow between lanes, that is not one of my questions. All of my work was run in a separate R jobs (Hora_Elizabeth_Final_Project_pike_job_class, Hora_Elizabeth_Final_Project_pike_job_speed, Hora_Elizabeth_Final_Project_pike_job_volume) in the attached in this submission. A brief schematic of what I did to process the speed and class is the image below (the first and second left_join() each having their own function to rename columns):



Solving the Data Issues


The processing for class went smoothly after defining my renaming functions and modified left_join() functions. However, the processing for speed was much more involved because locations AET09, AET10, and AET11 had different columns than AET12 and AET13 (shown in the image above). After defining additional functions, I was able to combine all observations together.


The first thing I notice is what I like to call the NASA Category, or the 9999+mph speed range. Upon looking at the data, there were surprisingly instances of people traveling at 13 times the speed of sound down the Mass Pike, but those strange data points were excluded in the data processing steps, so I do not have to worry about NASA or SpaceX dragging up the average speeds for the day. To estimate the speed of cars traveling through different locations on the Mass Pike, I used a the sum of a calculated weighted average of each speed range to get a rough estimate of the daily average speed. This was limited to daily because both class and speed were collected on a per day basis. This calculation was inspired by the types of natural abundance of isotopes calculations that I learned in General Chemistry as a baby freshman.

Outlining the Model Process

The first sets of models I created predicted the cars_per_hour in 2020 based on data from 2016-2019. I ran a linear model, a random forest model, a boosted tree model, another boosted tree model with modified parameters, a nearest neighbor model, and a nearest neighbor model with adjusted parameters. Each of these models, except for the linear model, has a dedicated RScript to run separately as jobs. I initially ran some models on my computer, but my Dad offered me a different computer with better RAM and memory to be able to handle more extensive models. After receiving the results for these models, I decided to attempt to model the daily average speed of cars in 2020 based on available data from 2016-2019. Comparing how the number of cars passing through data collection points to how the average speed has changed would bring insight into traffic patterns and whether or not congestion pricing is a realistic solution to managing traffic.


The distribution of points for cars_per_hour shows that data do not exhibit a linear relationship. Therefore, I would expect the linear model to perform poorly compared to the other modelling methods.

The distribution of points for vehicle class and speed shows that data do not exhibit a linear relationship. Therefore, I would expect the linear model to perform poorly compared to the other modelling methods.

The distribution of cars looks a lot like the overall distribution, likely because cars make up a bulk of the data.

Splitting the Data

I had enough data (a whole years worth) to manually set as the test set and four years worth to set as the training set. In the different model types, I used cars_per_hour from 2016-2019 to predict cars_per_hour in 2020. I also did the same thing with daily_sum from 2016-2019 to predict the daily_sum in 2020.

# Wrangling Volume Data
pike_volume_data <- pike_volume_processed_data %>% 
  filter(day_of_week != "Sunday") %>% 
  filter(day_of_week != "Saturday") %>% 
  mutate(year = year(full_date)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(cars_per_hour)) %>% 
  mutate(day_of_week = factor(day_of_week, 
                              levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday")
                                ))

# Wrangling Class and Speed Data
pike_class_data <- read_rds("pike_class_processed_data.rds") %>% 
  mutate(day_of_week = wday(full_date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)) %>% 
  filter(day_of_week != "Sunday") %>% 
  filter(day_of_week != "Saturday") %>% 
  mutate(year = year(full_date)) %>% 
  mutate(day_of_week = factor(day_of_week, 
                              levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday")
  )) %>% 
  filter(total != 0)



pike_speed_data <- read_rds("pike_speed_processed_data.rds") %>% 
  mutate(day_of_week = wday(full_date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)) %>% 
  filter(day_of_week != "Sunday") %>% 
  filter(day_of_week != "Saturday") %>% 
  mutate(year = year(full_date)) %>% 
  mutate(month = month(full_date)) %>% 
  mutate(day = day(full_date)) %>% 
  mutate(day_of_week = factor(day_of_week, 
                              levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday")
  )) %>% 
  filter(total != 0)

pike_class_speed_data <- left_join(
  pike_class_data,
  pike_speed_data,
  by = c("direction", "location", "day_of_week", "year", "full_date", "total")
)


pike_class_speed_data_avg_speed <- pike_class_speed_data %>% 
  group_by(total, direction, location, year, month, day) %>% 
  mutate(x0_20_mph_wt = x0_20_mph/total,
         x20_25_mph_wt = x20_25_mph/total * 25,
         x25_30_mph_wt = x25_30_mph/total * 30,
         x30_35_mph_wt = x30_35_mph/total * 35,
         x35_40_mph_wt = x35_40_mph/total * 40,
         x40_45_mph_wt = x40_45_mph/total * 45,
         x45_50_mph_wt = x45_50_mph/total * 50,
         x50_55_mph_wt = x50_55_mph/total * 55,
         x55_60_mph_wt = x55_60_mph/total * 60,
         x60_65_mph_wt = x60_65_mph/total * 65,
         x65_70_mph_wt = x65_70_mph/total * 70,
         x70_mph_wt = x70_mph/total * 75
         ) %>%
  select(contains("wt")) %>% 
  mutate(daily_sum = sum(c(x0_20_mph_wt, x20_25_mph_wt,
                         x25_30_mph_wt, x30_35_mph_wt,
                         x35_40_mph_wt, x40_45_mph_wt,
                         x45_50_mph_wt, x50_55_mph_wt,
                         x55_60_mph_wt, x60_65_mph_wt,
                         x65_70_mph_wt, x70_mph_wt))) %>% 
  select(-contains("wt"))


pike_class_speed_joined <- left_join(
  pike_class_speed_data_avg_speed,
  pike_class_speed_data,
  by = c("direction", "location", "year", "total", "day" = "date", "month")
) %>% 
  select(-day.y)


 
# Training Set for Volume
pike_volume_train <- pike_volume_data %>% 
  filter(year != 2020) %>% 
  select(-c(year))

# Testing Set for Volume

Looking at Model Results for Volume

Linear Model

# Pike recipe
pike_recipe_linear <- recipe(cars_per_hour ~ ., data = pike_volume_train) %>% 
  step_rm(full_date) %>% 
  step_dummy(c(day_of_week, direction, location)) %>% 
  step_ns(day, hour, month)


# Linear Model
linear_model <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("lm") 


# Test Workflow
pike_linear_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(linear_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(pike_recipe_linear)

# Fitting the results
test_results <- fit(pike_linear_workflow, pike_volume_train)

# Setting my rmse metric
linear_metric_set <- metric_set(rmse)

# Creating a prediction
predict(test_results, new_data = pike_volume_test) %>% 
  bind_cols(pike_volume_test %>% select(cars_per_hour)) %>% 
  linear_metric_set(truth = cars_per_hour, estimate = .pred)

When I finally look at the test data, interestingly enough, the distribution does indicate that speeds changed- people generally traveled faster with less cars on the road at the different points along the Mass Pike. In this sense, less cars on the roads seemed to lead to faster speeds. There is a major difference in average speeds between January and February of 2020 compared to previous January and February data from 2016-2019. When looking at the month of April, the difference is staggering. When looking at the total number of vehicles on the road, there were around 25,000 when normally there would be around 60,000. In order to travel 9mph faster, 40,000 cars had to be taken off the road each day. With public transportation being unreliable and often lacking coverage, it will be interesting to see how practical it is to take this many commuters off the roads beyond the pandemic. To only travel about 8mph faster, only 20,000 cars need to be taken off the roads, so this might be more practical. Additionally, the Mass Pike is a very simplistic highway in that there are no traffic lights or major bottleneck intersections along the highway. For other locations, like I-95, I-495, and Route 2, there are either major intersections or traffic lights (special to Route 2) that slow down traffic. There are unfortunately not very consistent data collection mechanisms along these locations, so it is difficult to judge how many cars would need to be taken off the roads for those average speeds to go up. The next steps would be to repeat this process for as many different locations as I could to see if less cars consistently equates to faster speeds on the roads.
